                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 8.  <span>Segmental frame shifting.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.sec4.fig3.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.sec4.fig3.caption1.p1"></a><p>(A)-Anterior shift at thoraco-lumbar transition: pararthrum entirely on preceding segment with diarthrum on iso-segment. First lumbar transverse process (LTP) (on L1) is bi-segmental (T13+L1). Transitional vertebra (T13) has no capitular rib articulation and no LTP. <em>Macropus rufus</em> (Metatheria) MCZ 6930. (B)-Anterior shift at cervico-thoracic transition: pararthrum entirely on preceding segment (C7) in <em>Sotalia fluviatilis</em> (Cetacea) FMNH 99612. (C)-Posterior shift in the thoracic region: pararthrum entirely on iso-segment and migrated dorsal to the border between the neural arch and the centrum (neuro-central suture)-these two features together are analogous to the condition in archosaurian reptiles. <em>Myrmecophaga tridactyla</em> (Pilosa) FMNH 49342. Oc–occipital, C-cervical, T-thoracic, L–lumbar, di–diarthrum, pa–pararthrum, nc–neuro-central suture, LTP–lumbar transverse process.</p>
